        <link rel="schema.DC" href="https://purl.org/DC/elements/1.0/" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="RadioGraphics" /><meta name="dc.Title" content="Valsalva Sinus Aneurysms: Findings at CT and MR Imaging1" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Aliye Ozsoyoglu  Bricker" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Bindu  Avutu" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Tan-Lucien H.  Mohammed" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Eric E.  Williamson" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Imran S.  Syed" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Paul R.  Julsrud" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Paul  Schoenhagen" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Jacobo  Kirsch" /><meta name="dc.Description" content="The CT and MR imaging appearances of Valsalva (aortic) sinus aneurysms are described, and the relevant cardiac anatomy, clinical features, potential complications, and treatment options are discussed." /><meta name="Description" content="The CT and MR imaging appearances of Valsalva (aortic) sinus aneurysms are described, and the relevant cardiac anatomy, clinical features, potential complications, and treatment options are discussed." /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Aneurysms of the Valsalva sinus (aortic sinus) can be congenital or acquired and are rare. They are more common among men than women and among Asians than other ethnic groups. Nonruptured aneurysms..." /><meta name="Description" content="Aneurysms of the Valsalva sinus (aortic sinus) can be congenital or acquired and are rare. They are more common among men than women and among Asians than other ethnic groups. Nonruptured aneurysms..." /><meta name="dc.Publisher" content=" Radiological Society of North America" /><meta name="dc.Date" scheme="WTN8601" content="2010-01-01" /><meta name="dc.Type" content="research-article" /><meta name="dc.Format" content="text/HTML" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="doi" content="10.1148/rg.301095719" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="publisher-id" content="0300099" /><meta 